title: Coach Dan Gable discusses Yellowblue LED lighting at his museum
description:
“Our new LED lights are the best, and I couldn’t believe how much they improved the museum,” states Dan Gable, the museum’s namesake and legendary gold medal Olympic wrestler, NCAA champion coach and Presidential Medal of Freedom Recipient. “The updated LED lighting highlights each display perfectly and offers an open, comfortable space visitors really want to spend time in and enjoy.” 

During a $1.5 million dollar remodel funded by donations, the National Wrestling Hall of Fame Dan Gable Museum in Waterloo, Iowa installed $100K in new, LED lights from yellowblue LED, replacing all of the old, incandescent lighting in the building. 

“After a seamless installation process, the new LED lights created an ambiance that really highlights the museum artifacts and provides a cooler, safer space for our employees and visitors,” states Coach Jim Miller, the Dan Gable National Wrestling Hall of Fame Director. “Best of all, we saved over 65% on our energy bills and eliminated the hassles and expense of bulb replacement and maintenance fees.”

The museum now uses approximately 65% less energy to power the new LED lighting and emits 70% less heat with the upgrade, saving thousands each year on their utility bills.

“As a huge fan of wrestling and all that Dan Gable has contributed to the world, especially our local area, it has been a huge honor to help the museum offer a better experience for visitors and reduce energy costs,” states Craig Schwienebart, yellowblue Eco Tech President.

Currently, yellowblue LED serves the entire Midwest and more and plans to expand significantly in 2022. To learn more, and see the exclusive interview with Coach Dan Gable, visit https://yellowblueled.com/coach-dan-gable-yellowblue-led/.

title: Learn about the yellowblue LED 2x4 ballast bypass
description:
Hi. My name is Kel Durham with Yellowblue LED. Right now, I'm going to show you guys how to change out the fixtures. The first thing you want to do is you want to take out all your bulbs. Once you have all your bulbs taken out, you'll want to disconnect the power from the ballast and cap it immediately. The black is going to be your power. So, you cut the black, separate it from all the other wires, and get it to your desired length. I'm just going to cut that there.

After that, you're going to do the same thing with the white wire - the negative. After that, you pretty much just get the entire fixture down from all existing wires. So, right there, we just bypassed the ballast. So, all your power is connected to this red and this white right here. So, what you're going to want to do is take out these old tombstones, replace them with new tombstones, and then piggy back each one to each other. And then one of the tombstones, you're going to have wires running out of. Your red is going to go to your red. And your blue is going to go to your white to provide the power since we bypassed the ballast. This is the step that takes the longest here. So, bear with me.

So, you're going to cut those to size?

Yes. You'll want to keep one color to one side, so my blues are on your guys’ left. So, I'll put this blue on the left again, piggy back it to this one here. I'll do the same thing with my reds except for the right-hand side.

And you can choose either this one or this one. I'll just do this one for convenience out of this little notch right here. It's all ready to be hooked up.

So, here's what your tombstones are going to look like after they're rewired. I've got my blues on the right hand of each tombstone. So, I've got the blue running to the blue here, this blue here running to this blue. I've got this blue piggy backed out to the power supply - the neutral. This is going to be my positive except these are all on the left. It's all ready to be installed now.

So, when I plug those bulbs in, it's immediate light?

You're going to put this end right here, labeled with the "L", on the end. This has got all our power. These are our single-ended tubes. I loaded all of my power to this right end here. So, make sure you're hooking up the right end to the right power.

title: Replace a T8 with a T8 LED and experience the benefits!
description:
We're going to show you now how to identify a fluorescent tube and how to open up a fixture. Every fixture is a little bit different. But on one side or the other, on the long end of the fixture, will be couple of tabs. Pull the tabs and carefully lower so as not to cause it to fall out.

Then, the next thing we're going to do is we're just going to spin our fluorescent tubes and pull down. You may have to angle it a little bit to get it out. Now, what we're looking for on each tube, this is how we're going to identify our products. On every single lighting product in the world, you'll see a stamp. It will tell you the type of product that it is along with the wattage that it's running. 

So, to do accurate walk throughs, this is exactly what we need to find on the products in the field. 

Okay?

And here we have our OptiFIT tube, which will run with or without a ballast. Just for the sake of showing you how much better the quality of LED lighting is, we'll throw it in, in place of the fluorescent tube that was out.

Now the beauty of an OptiFIT tube is if this ballast were ever to go bad, we could simply pop this cover, exposing the ballast, and clip the ballast and wire that right to the power source, making this essentially a decent fixture.
